{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 229 "2.  Polynomials:  Intercepts and Sign.  \+
There are several features about the graphs of polynomials which are i
mportant to track.  These features inform us about the behavior of the
 function.  Those features include the following:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 57 "    a.    x-intercepts of
 the function                   " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 129 "    \+
                   Those values where the graph crosses the x-axis.  T
hose points are solutions of the equation y = f(x) = 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    b.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the \+
function where the values of the function are positive" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "                       Those regions where the grap
h lies above the x-axis.  For a continuous function, and in particular
 for polynomials, these regions are bounded by the intercepts and may \+
stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    c.    re
gions (intervals) in the domain of the function where the values of th
e function are negative" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "             \+
          Those regions where the graph lies below the x-axis.  For a \+
continuous function, and in particular for polynomials, these regions \+
are bounded by the intercepts and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 36 "    d.   y-intercept of the function" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 107 "                       The value where t
he graph crosses the y-axis.  The value of the function when x = 0." }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 19 "    e.   end limits" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 384 "                       For a polynomial, its values will
 become either arbitrarily large in a positive sense or arbitrarily la
rge in a negative sense as the domain values tend to infinity.  Graphi
cally, the values on the graph will growth arbitrarily large positivel
y (go up off the graph) or arbitrarily large negative (go down off the
 graph) as the domain values tend to infinity.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 87 "                       Similar behavior holds true for ap
proaches to negative infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 150 "For each of the following polynomials,  \+
provide a graph of the polynomial.  Choose a range that will optimally
 represent the features of the graph.   " }{TEXT 268 4 "Also" }{TEXT 
-1 90 ", for each polynomial find each of the above five graphcial cha
racteristics (a.  thru e.):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 
